      <h2>Specifications</h2>
      <table>
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>Type</th><td>Cordless 18&nbsp;gauge narrow crown stapler, brushless</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Voltage</th><td>20V Max* (DCB battery platform)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Firing mode</th><td>Selectable &mdash; Sequential or Bump actuation</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Magazine</th><td>Straight, sliding; 100&nbsp;staple capacity</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Staple length</th><td>1/2&Prime; &ndash; 1‑1/2&Prime; (13&nbsp;mm &ndash; 38&nbsp;mm)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Staple gauge</th><td>18&nbsp;gauge</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Crown width</th><td>1/4&Prime; (6.3&nbsp;mm)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Height</th><td>11.4&Prime; (28.9&nbsp;cm)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Width</th><td>3.7&Prime; (9.3&nbsp;cm)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Length</th><td>10.1&Prime; (25.65&nbsp;cm)</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Weight</th><td>5.7&nbsp;lbs (2.5&nbsp;kg), without battery</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <p>Designed for driving 18&nbsp;gauge narrow crown staples into wooden workpieces &mdash; cabinetry, furniture, paneling, and flooring underlayment. No gas, compressor, or hose required. Do not use in wet conditions or in the presence of flammable liquids or gases.</p>

      <h2>Safety</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Read all safety warnings and all instructions. Failure to follow them may result in electric shock, fire, and/or serious injury. Always assume the tool contains fasteners.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li><strong>Never point the tool at yourself or anyone else.</strong> Unexpected triggering will discharge a fastener.</li>
        <li><strong>Do not actuate unless the tool is firmly against the workpiece.</strong> Otherwise the fastener may be deflected away from your target.</li>
        <li><strong>Remove the battery pack and empty the magazine</strong> before clearing a jam, making adjustments, performing maintenance, or passing the tool to another person.</li>
        <li>Wear ANSI Z87.1 eye protection (CAN/CSA Z94.3) with side shields, and ANSI S12.6 (S3.19) hearing protection. Everyday eyeglasses are not safety glasses.</li>
        <li>Hold the tool by insulated gripping surfaces when fasteners may contact hidden wiring. A live wire will energize exposed metal parts.</li>
        <li>Do not use this stapler to fasten electrical cables &mdash; it may damage insulation and create shock or fire hazards.</li>
        <li>Do not drive staples near the edge of material; the workpiece may split and the staple may ricochet or follow the grain (a &ldquo;shiner&rdquo;) out the side. Drive the chisel point perpendicular to the grain.</li>
        <li>Do not drive staples onto the heads of other fasteners or at too steep an angle &mdash; strong recoil, jams, or ricochets can result.</li>
        <li>Always engage the trigger lock‑off when the tool is not in immediate use, and never carry the tool with a finger on the trigger.</li>
        <li>In Bump mode, beware of unintentional double fires from recoil &mdash; allow the tool to recoil fully after each shot and do not push the tool against the work with strong force.</li>
        <li>Do not drive staples blindly into walls or floors; fasteners hitting live wires, plumbing, or other obstructions can cause injury.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="note">
        Never spray or apply lubricants or cleaning solvents inside the tool &mdash; this can seriously affect its life and performance.
      </div>

