      <h2>Battery</h2>

      <p>The battery pack is not fully charged out of the carton &mdash; charge it fully before first use on a compatible DeWALT charger.</p>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn681/fig_battery_install.png" alt="Battery pack (13) being slid into the bottom of the stapler handle, with the release button (14) called out for removal" />
        <figcaption>Fig. E &mdash; installing and removing the battery pack</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>To install, align the pack with the rails inside the handle and slide it in until it is firmly seated and does not disengage.</li>
        <li>To remove, press the release button <strong>(14)</strong> and firmly pull the pack out of the handle.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="note">
        Do not store the tool with the battery pack installed. For best battery life, store packs out of the tool and charger in a cool, dry place &mdash; never below 40&nbsp;&deg;F (4.5&nbsp;&deg;C) or above 104&nbsp;&deg;F (40&nbsp;&deg;C).
      </div>

      <h2>Loading the Tool</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Keep the tool pointed away from yourself and others. Always remove the battery pack before loading or unloading, and never load with the contact trip or trigger activated.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn681/fig_loading.png" alt="A strip of staples being loaded into the open sliding magazine (6) with the magazine latch (15) shown at the rear" />
        <figcaption>Fig. G/I &mdash; loading staples into the sliding magazine</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Press the magazine latch <strong>(15)</strong> and open the sliding magazine <strong>(6)</strong> fully.</li>
        <li>Load the staple strip so the crown of the staple sits against the inside surface of the magazine.</li>
        <li>Close the sliding magazine until the latch clips snugly.</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Unloading</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Press the magazine latch <strong>(15)</strong> and open the sliding magazine fully.</li>
        <li>Tip the tool up until the staples slide freely out of the bottom of the magazine.</li>
        <li>Confirm no loose staples remain, then close the magazine fully.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        <strong>Dry‑fire lock out:</strong> when no fasteners are visible in the fastener window <strong>(16)</strong>, the tool is running low and will lock out, refusing to actuate until more staples are loaded.
      </div>

      <h2>Operating</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Keep fingers away from the trigger when not driving staples. Never carry the tool with a finger on the trigger. When the motor is running, pulling the trigger or depressing the contact trip will drive a staple.
      </div>

      <h3>Trigger Lock-off</h3>
      <p>Each stapler has a trigger lock‑off <strong>(2)</strong>. Pushed to the right, it locks the trigger and bypasses power to the motor, preventing firing. Pushed to the left, the tool is fully operational. Always lock it off whenever adjustments are made or the tool is not in immediate use.</p>

      <h3>Proper Hand Position</h3>
      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn681/fig_hand_position.png" alt="Stapler held with one hand firmly on the pistol grip, ready to control recoil as a fastener is driven" />
        <figcaption>Fig. F &mdash; proper hand position; always hold securely in anticipation of a sudden reaction</figcaption>
      </div>

      <h3>Mode Selection</h3>
      <p>The stapler can fire using <strong>sequential</strong> or <strong>bump</strong> actuation, set with the selector switch <strong>(7)</strong>. Look at the switch to confirm the mode before operating.</p>

      <h4>Sequential actuation (single‑staple icon)</h4>
      <p>Use for intermittent stapling where careful, accurate placement and depth control are needed. Sequential mode delivers the maximum power for the longest staples.</p>
      <ol>
        <li>Slide the selector switch <strong>(7)</strong> to expose the single‑staple icon.</li>
        <li>Fully depress the nosepiece against the work surface (the motor will start).</li>
        <li>Pull the trigger &mdash; the staple drives into the work surface.</li>
        <li>Release the trigger, then lift the nosepiece off the work surface.</li>
        <li>Repeat for the next staple.</li>
      </ol>
      <div class="note">
        The contact trip must be depressed and then the trigger pulled for each staple, followed by releasing both after each staple.
      </div>

      <h4>Bump action (triple‑staple icon)</h4>
      <p>Intended for rapid stapling on flat, stationary surfaces &mdash; most effective with shorter staples. Slide the selector switch <strong>(7)</strong> to expose the triple‑staple icon. Two methods are available:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Place actuation:</strong> depress the contact trip against the work surface, then depress the trigger. A staple drives each time the trigger is pulled as long as the contact trip stays depressed.</li>
        <li><strong>Bump actuation:</strong> depress and hold the trigger, then push the contact trip against the work surface. As long as the trigger is held, a staple drives every time the contact trip is depressed.</li>
      </ul>
      <div class="warning">
        In bump action, beware of double fires from recoil. Allow the tool to recoil fully after each shot, do not engage the work with strong force, and keep the tool under control at all times.
      </div>

      <h2>Adjusting Depth</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        To reduce the risk of injury from accidental actuation: always remove the battery pack, engage the trigger lock‑off, and avoid contact with the trigger while adjusting depth.
      </div>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn681/fig_depth_adjust.png" alt="Side of the stapler showing the depth adjustment wheel (3) and the staple depth indicator (12)" />
        <figcaption>Fig. J &mdash; depth adjustment wheel (3) and depth indicator (12)</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>To drive the staple <strong>shallower</strong>, rotate the depth adjustment wheel <strong>(3)</strong> away from the nose of the stapler.</li>
        <li>To sink the staple <strong>deeper</strong>, rotate the wheel toward the nose of the stapler.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Headlights and Indicators</h2>
      <p>A headlight <strong>(4)</strong> is located on each side of the stapler. They turn on when the battery is inserted, the trigger is pulled, or the contact trip is depressed, and shut off automatically after 20&nbsp;seconds unless the tool stays in use. They light the work surface and are not intended as flashlights.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Low battery:</strong> the left‑side headlight flashes four times, then shuts down.</li>
        <li><strong>Jammed staple:</strong> the right‑side headlight flashes continually.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Clearing a Jammed Staple</h2>

      <p>If a staple jams in the nosepiece, keep the tool pointed away from yourself and others.</p>

      <div class="figure">
        <img src="/manuals/dewalt-dcn681/fig_jam_clear.png" alt="Top of the stapler nose showing the stall release lever (11) used to slide the driver blade back when it is stuck in the down position" />
        <figcaption>Fig. L &mdash; stall release lever (11) for resetting the driver blade</figcaption>
      </div>

      <ol>
        <li>Remove the battery pack and engage the trigger lock‑off.</li>
        <li>Press the magazine latch <strong>(15)</strong> and remove any loaded staples.</li>
        <li>Visually check inside the magazine for jammed staples.</li>
        <li>Remove the bent staple, using pliers if necessary.</li>
        <li>If the driver blade is in the down position, cycle the stall release lever <strong>(11)</strong> with enough force to fully slide it to the other end of its slot.</li>
        <li>Reload the staples (see Loading the Tool).</li>
        <li>Reinsert the battery pack.</li>
      </ol>

      <div class="note">
        The tool disables itself and will not reset until the battery pack has been removed and reinserted. If staples continue to jam frequently, have the tool serviced by an authorized DeWALT service center.
      </div>

      <h2>Cold and Hot Weather</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Below freezing:</strong> keep the tool as warm as possible before use, and actuate it 5 or 6 times into scrap lumber before starting work.</li>
        <li><strong>Hot weather:</strong> the tool should operate normally, but keep it out of direct sunlight &mdash; excessive heat can deteriorate bumpers and other rubber parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Maintenance</h2>

      <div class="warning">
        Turn the unit off and remove the battery pack before any adjustment, maintenance, or accessory change. An accidental start‑up can cause injury.
      </div>

      <ul>
        <li>Blow dirt and dust out of all air vents with clean, dry air at least once a week. Wear ANSI Z87.1 eye protection while doing so.</li>
        <li>Never use solvents or harsh chemicals on non‑metallic parts &mdash; they weaken the plastic. Clean with a cloth dampened only with water and mild soap.</li>
        <li>Never let liquid get inside the tool or immerse any part of it.</li>
        <li>Never spray or apply lubricants or solvents inside the tool.</li>
        <li>The charger and battery pack are not serviceable. For safety and reliability, have repairs, maintenance, and adjustment performed by a DeWALT factory or authorized service center using identical replacement parts.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Belt Hook</h2>
      <p>The integrated belt hook <strong>(8)</strong> can be attached to either side of the tool for left‑ or right‑handed use. To switch sides, remove the battery pack, remove the screw from the opposite side, reassemble the hook on the other side, and replace the battery. The hook can be removed entirely if not wanted.</p>

